{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477631"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:03:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:03:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14624"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14624"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.46,0.01,0.16,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7317"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57511"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7317"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14624"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42970"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2859"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18168"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57511"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-week-old girl presents to the Emergency department with a one-week history of red circular patches on her face. She was born at term following an uncomplicated pregnancy and delivery via a home birth and has not been seen by other medical professionals as yet. Her mother has Sj\u00f6gren syndrome. The baby takes no regular medications. She has not had any vaccinations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple erythematous annular plaques with slight scale on her forehead, cheeks, and around her eyes, with periorbital erythema. The lesions are more prominent after she has been outside. Her heart rate is regular with no murmurs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-nuclear antibody test","Maternal anti-Ro/SSA antibodies","Blood culture","Skin biopsy","Complement levels"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with characteristic features of neonatal lupus erythematosus (NLE), including photosensitive annular plaques and periorbital erythema (\u0027racoon eye\u0027) in a child born to a mother with an autoimmune condition. Mother\u0027s may be asymptomatic.  Rashes may be present at birth or develop during the first few weeks of life.  The diagnosis is primarily clinical and confirmed by the presence of maternal autoantibodies.  The rash typically resolve spontaneously before the first year of life as maternal antibodies disappear if there is only cutaneous involvement.  Babies may also present with hepatic or cardiac involvement.  Cardiac screening is essential as congenital heart block, if present, is permanent and may require a pacemaker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal anti-Ro/SSA antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are diagnostic of NLE. These antibodies cross the placenta during pregnancy and can be detected in both the mother and infant in up to 90% of patients. The presence of these antibodies, along with typical clinical features, confirms the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely necessary in NLE as the clinical presentation and maternal antibody status are usually sufficient for diagnosis. It may demonstrate inflammatory infiltrate but other infectious conditions may also demonstrate similar findings on biopsy.  Additionally, performing a biopsy on an infant is invasive and should be avoided if possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-nuclear antibody\u003C/strong\u003E testing in the infant is not helpful as these antibodies are maternally derived and will be present regardless of whether the infant has NLE. They do not confirm the specific diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E would not be helpful in diagnosis NLE.  It is not a bacterial infection and the infant does not present with infectious symptoms. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplement levels\u003C/strong\u003E are not specifically helpful in diagnosing NLE. While complement consumption may occur in systemic lupus erythematosus, it is not a characteristic feature of the neonatal form.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neonatal lupus erythematosus typically presents with annular erythematous plaques in sun-exposed areas.","Maternal anti-Ro/SSA antibodies are diagnostic of neonatal lupus erythematosus."],"references":["Hon KL, Leung AK. Neonatal lupus erythematosus. Autoimmune Dis. 2012;2012:301274.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3437607/","Yokogawa N, Sumitomo N, Miura M, Shibuya K, Nagai H, Goto M, Murashima A.  Neonatal lupus erythematosus.  Japanese Journal of Clinical Immunology. 2017: 40 (2). Available at: https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/jsci/40/2/40_124/_article/-char/en"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42970"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14624"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42970"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-26T17:43:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-26T17